    {
      "title": "Introduction to Angular",
      "left": [
        {
          "name": "What is Angular?",
          "discription": "<p>Angular is an open-source web application framework primarily maintained by Google and a community of developers. It is used for building dynamic, single-page web applications (SPAs) and progressive web applications (PWAs). Angular is based on TypeScript, a superset of JavaScript, which adds static typing and other advanced features to the language.</p><p>Angular provides a robust set of tools and features to simplify the development of complex web applications. Some key components and concepts of Angular include:</p><ol><li><b>Components: </b>Angular applications are built using components, which are self-contained units responsible for handling a specific part of the user interface (UI). Each component combines HTML templates, TypeScript code, and CSS styles to create a reusable, isolated piece of functionality.</li><li><b>Templates: </b>Angular's templates are written in HTML and define the structure of the user interface. Templates can include data bindings, event handlers, and other directives to interact with the component's logic.</li><li><b>Directives: </b>Directives are markers on elements in the template that instruct Angular to attach specific behaviors to those elements. Angular has built-in directives like ngIf, ngFor, and ngModel, which provide conditional rendering, iteration, and two-way data binding, respectively.</li><li><b>Services: </b>Services in Angular are used to share data and business logic between components. They provide a way to keep components lean and maintain separation of concerns in the application.</li><li><b>Dependency Injection (DI): </b>Angular's DI system helps manage the dependencies of different components and services. It promotes the idea of injecting required dependencies into a component instead of creating them within the component itself.</li><li><b>Routing: </b>Angular provides a powerful routing module that allows developers to implement client-side navigation. This enables users to move between different views or pages within the application without triggering a full-page reload.</li><li><b>Modules: </b>Angular applications are organized into modules. Each module encapsulates related components, services, and other pieces of functionality, making the application more modular and maintainable.</li><li><b>Forms: </b>Angular offers form handling capabilities, including form validation, to manage user input and interaction with the application.</li></ol><p>Angular has gone through multiple versions, and at the time of my last update in September 2021, the latest stable version was Angular 12. However, new versions may have been released since then. It's essential to check the official Angular website or repository for the most up-to-date information.</p>"
        }
      ],
      "right": [
        {
          "name": "Advantages and key features of Angular",
          "discription": "<p>Angular is a <strong>popular front-end JavaScript framework</strong> maintained by Google. It offers many advantages such as <em>two-way data binding</em>, dependency injection, and a modular architecture, making it suitable for building large-scale applications.</p>"
        }
      ]
